gamentum venosum","Lateral umbilical ligament","Round ligament of the liver","Median umbilical ligament"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eround ligament of the liver\u003C/strong\u003E (ligamentum teres hepatis) is the fibrous remnant of the umbilical vein. It extends from the umbilicus to the left branch of the portal vein.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent different fetal remnants:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eligamentum arteriosum\u003C/strong\u003E is the remnant of the ductus arteriosus\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eligamentum venosum\u003C/strong\u003E is the remnant of the ductus venosus\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral umbilical ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E are the remnants of the umbilical arteries\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian umbilical ligament\u003C/strong\u003E is the remnant of the urachus\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these remnant structures is important as they serve as important anatomical landmarks and help trace the path of fetal circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The round ligament of the liver is the remnant of the umbilical vein that carried oxygenated blood from the placenta to the fetus during development.","The round ligament extends from the umbilicus to the left branch of the portal vein."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48770"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15953"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48770"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T13:16:19+10:30","updatedAt":"20